1
00:03:20,335 --> 00:03:23,270
An article, which I believe
appeared in a newspaper,

2
00:03:23,338 --> 00:03:25,272
asked why, since you are,

3
00:03:25,340 --> 00:03:28,776
or it would seem that you are in effect,

4
00:03:28,844 --> 00:03:30,277
the mayor of Chicago,

5
00:03:30,345 --> 00:03:33,280
you've not simply been
appointed to that position.

6
00:03:36,185 --> 00:03:38,483
Well, I'll tell you, you know, it's touching.

7
00:03:38,554 --> 00:03:41,489
Like a lot of things in life,

8
00:03:41,557 --> 00:03:43,491
we laugh because it's funny,

9
00:03:43,559 --> 00:03:45,993
and we laugh because it's true.

10
00:03:46,061 --> 00:03:48,996
Some people say, "Put that man in jail.

11
00:03:49,064 --> 00:03:51,999
What does he think he is doing?"

12
00:03:52,067 --> 00:03:54,001
What I hope I'm doing...

13
00:03:54,069 --> 00:03:56,833
here's where your English paper's got a point...

14
00:03:56,905 --> 00:04:00,363
is I'm responding to the will of the people.

15
00:04:00,442 --> 00:04:01,568
People will drink.

16
00:04:01,643 --> 00:04:02,974
We all know that.

17
00:04:03,045 --> 00:04:05,878
And all I do is act on that.

18
00:04:05,948 --> 00:04:07,779
All this talk of bootlegging...

19
00:04:07,850 --> 00:04:09,283
What is bootlegging?

20
00:04:09,351 --> 00:04:11,285
On the boat, it's bootlegging.

21
00:04:11,353 --> 00:04:13,287
On Lake Shore Drive, it's hospitality.

22
00:04:13,355 --> 00:04:14,788
I'm a businessman.

23
00:04:14,857 --> 00:04:16,791
And what of your reputation

24
00:04:16,859 --> 00:04:19,657
that you control your business through violence,

25
00:04:19,728 --> 00:04:22,492
that those that don't purchase your products

26
00:04:22,564 --> 00:04:24,532
are dealt with violently?

27
00:04:29,671 --> 00:04:31,229
It's all right.

28
00:04:32,908 --> 00:04:35,843
I grew up in a tough neighborhood.

29
00:04:35,911 --> 00:04:38,675
We used to say, you can get further

30
00:04:38,747 --> 00:04:41,511
with a kind word and a gun

31
00:04:41,583 --> 00:04:43,847
than with just a kind word.

32
00:04:43,919 --> 00:04:46,854
In that neighborhood, it might have been true.

33
00:04:46,922 --> 00:04:48,856
Sometimes a reputation follows you.

34
00:04:48,924 --> 00:04:51,859
There is violence in Chicago, of course,

35
00:04:51,927 --> 00:04:55,863
but not by me and not by anybody I employ

36
00:04:55,931 --> 00:04:57,899
because it's not good business.

37
00:05:28,797 --> 00:05:32,233
Leave us alone down here.
We're getting along fine.

38
00:05:32,301 --> 00:05:34,235
We have everything we need.

39
00:05:34,303 --> 00:05:37,238
The green beer you're peddling ain't any good.

40
00:05:37,306 --> 00:05:39,740
It ain't supposed to be good.

41
00:05:39,808 --> 00:05:41,742
It's supposed to be bought.

42
00:05:41,810 --> 00:05:43,437
I'm not buying any.

43
00:05:46,748 --> 00:05:49,182
Don't worry about it, Pops.

44
00:05:49,251 --> 00:05:50,878
We won't come back.

45
00:05:53,322 --> 00:05:56,018
And how's everyone
at your house today?

46
00:05:56,091 --> 00:05:57,183
They're fine.

47
00:05:57,259 --> 00:05:58,988
Your mama well?

48
00:05:59,061 --> 00:06:00,995
She has a little cold.

49
00:06:01,063 --> 00:06:03,088
Oh, she does, huh?

50
00:06:04,433 --> 00:06:06,367
I'm sorry to hear that.

51
00:06:06,435 --> 00:06:08,096
But she'll be all right.

52
00:06:12,507 --> 00:06:14,372
Here you go.

53
00:06:14,443 --> 00:06:15,375
Thank you.

54
00:06:15,444 --> 00:06:18,413
Oh, that's all right, sweetie.

55
00:06:18,480 --> 00:06:20,880
You be careful crossing the street.

56
00:06:20,949 --> 00:06:22,348
Mister!

57
00:06:22,417 --> 00:06:23,441
Mister!

58
00:06:23,518 --> 00:06:25,713
Hey, mister!

59
00:06:25,787 --> 00:06:26,719
Wait!

60
00:06:26,788 --> 00:06:28,881
Mister, wait!

61
00:06:28,957 --> 00:06:30,219
You forgot your brief...

62
00:07:35,190 --> 00:07:38,455
Yes. I heard it on the radio.

63
00:07:39,895 --> 00:07:41,123
I know.

64
00:07:42,698 --> 00:07:45,633
Now it's time to go to work.

65
00:07:53,775 --> 00:07:56,141
Go make a good first impression.

66
00:08:05,220 --> 00:08:06,915
I love you, Eliot.

67
00:08:14,629 --> 00:08:16,290
Now, shoo.

68
00:08:16,665 --> 00:08:18,758
Eliot Ness...

69
00:08:18,834 --> 00:08:21,860
special agent of the Treasury Department.

70
00:08:21,937 --> 00:08:23,131
Mr. Ness.

71
00:08:23,205 --> 00:08:24,638
Thank you, Chief.

72
00:08:24,706 --> 00:08:27,641
At the request of the city of Chicago,

73
00:08:27,709 --> 00:08:29,142
the federal government,

74
00:08:29,211 --> 00:08:31,645
specifically the Department of the Treasury,

75
00:08:31,713 --> 00:08:33,146
has inaugurated a program

76
00:08:33,215 --> 00:08:36,150
to deal with the flow of illegal liquor

77
00:08:36,218 --> 00:08:38,152
and the violence it creates.

78
00:08:38,220 --> 00:08:40,654
Of what does this program consist?

79
00:08:40,722 --> 00:08:42,656
I and other Treasury agents

80
00:08:42,724 --> 00:08:45,659
will work with the Chicago police and other...

81
00:08:45,727 --> 00:08:48,161
Isn't this just another showpiece program?

82
00:08:48,230 --> 00:08:51,165
What do you think about prohibition, Mr. Ness?

83
00:08:51,233 --> 00:08:53,167
Do you drink, Mr. Ness?

84
00:08:53,235 --> 00:08:54,668
Answer the questions.

85
00:08:54,736 --> 00:08:56,101
It's not a showpiece.

86
00:08:56,171 --> 00:08:57,604
And I'll tell you

87
00:08:57,672 --> 00:09:00,106
exactly how I feel about prohibition.

88
00:09:00,175 --> 00:09:02,609
It's the law of the land.

89
00:09:02,677 --> 00:09:05,111
Do you consider yourself a crusader?

90
00:09:05,180 --> 00:09:07,114
What qualifications do you have?

91
00:09:07,182 --> 00:09:09,616
Do you have any political ambitions?

92
00:09:09,684 --> 00:09:11,845
All right, boys.
That's enough.

93
00:09:11,920 --> 00:09:13,080
Excuse me.

94
00:09:13,155 --> 00:09:16,090
Mr. Ness. What are your real plans?

95
00:09:16,158 --> 00:09:19,093
You'll have to read about it in the paper.

96
00:09:19,161 --> 00:09:22,096
Listen, let me ride along with you.

97
00:09:22,164 --> 00:09:23,995
No. Can't help you.

98
00:09:24,065 --> 00:09:27,000
Mr. Ness. Lieutenant Olveson, the flying squad.

99
00:09:27,068 --> 00:09:30,003
Are you ready to meet the men?

100
00:09:30,071 --> 00:09:31,766
Well...

101
00:09:31,840 --> 00:09:33,569
Yes, I am.

102
00:09:43,174 --> 00:09:46,109
I have one more thing to say.

103
00:09:50,481 --> 00:09:53,917
I know that many of you take a drink.

104
00:09:53,985 --> 00:09:57,421
What you've done before today is not my concern.

105
00:09:57,488 --> 00:09:59,922
But now we must be pure,

106
00:09:59,991 --> 00:10:02,425
and I want you to stop.

107
00:10:02,493 --> 00:10:03,926
It's not a question

108
00:10:03,995 --> 00:10:06,930
of whether or not it's a harmless drink.

109
00:10:06,998 --> 00:10:08,932
It's against the law, gentlemen.

110
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:11,798
As we are going to enforce the law,

111
00:10:11,869 --> 00:10:14,133
we must do first by example.

112
00:10:18,776 --> 00:10:20,209
Are there any questions?

113
00:10:22,580 --> 00:10:23,638
Good.

114
00:10:23,715 --> 00:10:25,444
The Department of the Treasury

115
00:10:25,516 --> 00:10:28,713
has had a man undercover here for some time.

116
00:10:28,786 --> 00:10:31,118
We've received word from this informant

117
00:10:31,189 --> 00:10:34,454
of a large shipment of
Canadian whiskey to Chicago.

118
00:10:34,525 --> 00:10:37,289
I hope you've signed on for some action.

119
00:10:37,362 --> 00:10:38,954
You're going to get it.

120
00:10:44,836 --> 00:10:47,270
Remember, the liquor cases are marked

121
00:10:47,338 --> 00:10:49,272
with a red maple leaf.

122
00:10:49,340 --> 00:10:50,329
Yes, sir.

123
00:10:50,408 --> 00:10:53,343
The Treasury agent is in a gray suit.

124
00:10:53,411 --> 00:10:55,936
He is not to be arrested.

125
00:10:56,013 --> 00:10:57,446
A gray suit.

126
00:10:57,515 --> 00:10:59,449
I think that's about it.

127
00:10:59,517 --> 00:11:00,950
Are your men ready?

128
00:11:01,018 --> 00:11:02,451
Yes, sir. They are.

129
00:11:02,520 --> 00:11:03,782
Good.

130
00:11:09,694 --> 00:11:10,626
At ease.

131
00:11:10,695 --> 00:11:13,129
Smoke 'em if you got 'em.

132
00:11:19,604 --> 00:11:21,037
How are we doing?

133
00:11:21,105 --> 00:11:22,037
O.K.

134
00:11:27,612 --> 00:11:29,546
Want part of a sandwich?

135
00:11:29,614 --> 00:11:31,047
No, thank you, sir.

136
00:11:37,889 --> 00:11:38,821
You nervous?

137
00:11:38,890 --> 00:11:39,879
No, sir.

138
00:11:42,393 --> 00:11:44,327
Been with the unit long?

139
00:11:44,395 --> 00:11:45,828
A short while.

140
00:11:47,465 --> 00:11:50,400
I suppose we all want to do well.

141
00:11:50,468 --> 00:11:51,799
Yes, sir.

142
00:11:55,907 --> 00:11:56,771
[Chuckles]

143
00:11:56,841 --> 00:11:59,639
A message from my wife.

144
00:12:01,479 --> 00:12:02,411
You married?

145
00:12:02,480 --> 00:12:04,778
Yes, sir, I am.

146
00:12:04,849 --> 00:12:06,783
Nice to be married, huh?

147
00:12:22,233 --> 00:12:23,666
What is it?

148
00:12:25,102 --> 00:12:27,002
Just follow me.

149
00:12:38,616 --> 00:12:41,176
[Dog Barks]

150
00:13:08,646 --> 00:13:11,410
Federal officer.
Hands in the air.

151
00:13:11,482 --> 00:13:12,949
Get them up.

152
00:13:13,017 --> 00:13:14,484
Drop it.

153
00:13:14,552 --> 00:13:16,520
I can't...

154
00:13:18,122 --> 00:13:19,054
Mr. Ness.

155
00:13:19,123 --> 00:13:22,456
Look, I was just...
Jeez, I'm sorry.

156
00:13:24,662 --> 00:13:28,098
Listen, listen.
I can do a lot for you.

157
00:13:28,165 --> 00:13:31,293
I get the big scoop.
You make a big splash.

158
00:13:31,369 --> 00:13:32,859
Get yourself some support.

159
00:13:32,937 --> 00:13:34,370
What do you say?

160
00:13:34,438 --> 00:13:36,030
Let me help you.

161
00:13:36,107 --> 00:13:37,597
O.K. Just shut up.

162
00:14:04,335 --> 00:14:05,632
All right, now!

163
00:14:05,703 --> 00:14:07,694
Let's do some good!

164
00:14:19,083 --> 00:14:21,142
Let's get 'em.
Come on, guys.

165
00:14:21,218 --> 00:14:22,515
Hold it right there!

166
00:14:24,922 --> 00:14:26,355
Federal officer.

167
00:14:26,424 --> 00:14:27,857
You're under arrest

168
00:14:27,925 --> 00:14:30,359
for violations of the Volstead Act.

169
00:14:43,874 --> 00:14:45,000
Preseuski.

170
00:14:47,445 --> 00:14:48,537
Excuse me. Excuse me.

171
00:14:48,613 --> 00:14:51,309
No one's allowed in here.

172
00:14:51,382 --> 00:14:52,314
Mr. Ness!

173
00:14:52,383 --> 00:14:53,714
It's all right.

174
00:14:53,784 --> 00:14:56,252
Let... Let him through here.

175
00:14:57,521 --> 00:15:00,217
You want to take your picture?
Take it now.

176
00:15:02,627 --> 00:15:03,559
You ready?

177
00:15:03,628 --> 00:15:04,560
Ready.

178
00:15:30,921 --> 00:15:32,855
Liquor, huh?

179
00:15:34,925 --> 00:15:36,916
Get him out of here.

180
00:15:36,994 --> 00:15:39,019
Tear the place apart.

181
00:15:39,096 --> 00:15:41,530
I mean now!
Get him out!

182
00:15:41,599 --> 00:15:42,588
Yes, sir.

183
00:15:46,237 --> 00:15:48,034
That means you, too.

184
00:17:13,963 --> 00:17:16,898
Now, what do you think you're doing? Hmm?

185
00:17:16,966 --> 00:17:19,400
You want to throw your garbage?

186
00:17:19,468 --> 00:17:22,403
Throw it in the damn trash basket.

187
00:17:22,471 --> 00:17:26,339
Don't you have more important things to do?

188
00:17:26,409 --> 00:17:27,535
Yeah.

189
00:17:28,911 --> 00:17:31,846
But I'm not doing them right now.

190
00:17:31,914 --> 00:17:33,814
We understand each other?

191
00:17:38,788 --> 00:17:40,813
O.K., pal, why the mahoska?

192
00:17:42,391 --> 00:17:44,222
Why are you packing the gun?

193
00:17:44,293 --> 00:17:45,726
I'm a Treasury officer.

194
00:17:49,532 --> 00:17:50,794
All right.

195
00:17:52,368 --> 00:17:55,303
Just remember what we talked about, now.

196
00:17:59,508 --> 00:18:01,100
Hey. Wait a minute.

197
00:18:01,177 --> 00:18:06,513
What kind of police you have in this damn city?

198
00:18:06,582 --> 00:18:08,914
You turned your back on an armed man.

199
00:18:08,985 --> 00:18:10,452
You're a Treasury officer.

200
00:18:10,519 --> 00:18:13,784
How do you know?
I just told you that.

201
00:18:13,856 --> 00:18:16,791
Who would claim to be that who was not?

202
00:18:21,864 --> 00:18:23,798
What's your name and unit?

203
00:18:29,138 --> 00:18:30,571
It's right here.

204
00:18:33,109 --> 00:18:34,906
You got a beef?

205
00:18:34,977 --> 00:18:36,410
What is it?

206
00:18:37,880 --> 00:18:40,678
How did you know I had a gun?

207
00:18:40,750 --> 00:18:44,311
What, you want a free lesson in police work?

208
00:18:48,324 --> 00:18:49,382
No.

209
00:18:53,462 --> 00:18:55,396
Are you O.K., pal?

210
00:18:56,532 --> 00:18:59,467
I had a rough day on the job.

211
00:18:59,535 --> 00:19:00,729
Ah.

212
00:19:00,803 --> 00:19:02,896
Are you going home now?

213
00:19:02,972 --> 00:19:04,564
I was about to.

214
00:19:07,243 --> 00:19:09,177
Well, then you just fulfilled

215
00:19:09,245 --> 00:19:11,611
the first rule of law enforcement.

216
00:19:14,850 --> 00:19:18,342
Make sure when your shift is over,

217
00:19:18,421 --> 00:19:19,854
you go home alive.

218
00:19:19,922 --> 00:19:21,856
Here endeth the lesson.

219
00:20:20,816 --> 00:20:23,751
We got $100,000 there for 40 barrels.

220
00:20:23,819 --> 00:20:26,253
Make sure there are no empties.

221
00:20:26,322 --> 00:20:28,256
I'll give you the ledger.

222
00:20:28,324 --> 00:20:30,258
Everything is in the book.

223
00:20:30,326 --> 00:20:32,419
55 gallons to a barrel.

224
00:20:45,808 --> 00:20:47,332
It's Eddie.

225
00:20:47,409 --> 00:20:48,842
Come in, Eddie.

226
00:21:03,425 --> 00:21:05,689
[Chuckling]

227
00:21:12,334 --> 00:21:15,770
So he gets into the snowplow, and he says,

228
00:21:15,838 --> 00:21:17,669
"Let's do some good."

229
00:21:18,774 --> 00:21:20,708
And then we bust through...

230
00:22:09,525 --> 00:22:11,891
Mr. Ness?

231
00:22:11,961 --> 00:22:13,019
Yes?

232
00:22:13,095 --> 00:22:15,563
I came here to thank you.

233
00:22:17,099 --> 00:22:18,327
It was...

234
00:22:18,467 --> 00:22:22,096
my little girl that got killed with that bomb.

235
00:22:24,640 --> 00:22:26,540
I'm... I'm sorry.
Please.

236
00:22:28,210 --> 00:22:29,973
I'm... I'm so sorry.

237
00:22:31,680 --> 00:22:33,113
You see, it's...

238
00:22:33,182 --> 00:22:36,049
because I know that you have children, too...

239
00:22:36,118 --> 00:22:39,383
and that this is real for you

240
00:22:39,488 --> 00:22:43,151
that these men caused this tragedy.

241
00:22:43,225 --> 00:22:47,161
And I know you will put a stop to them.

242
00:22:47,229 --> 00:22:49,823
I know you'll do that now.

243
00:23:29,004 --> 00:23:30,938
[Knock On Door]

244
00:23:46,265 --> 00:23:47,926
What do you want?

245
00:23:48,000 --> 00:23:50,127
I'd like to talk to you.

246
00:23:52,271 --> 00:23:53,363
Come in.

247
00:23:57,777 --> 00:24:01,076
I need a small group of men, starting with you...

248
00:24:01,147 --> 00:24:05,106
Ness, I am just a poor beat cop.

249
00:24:05,184 --> 00:24:09,086
Now, how can *I* help *you*?

250
00:24:09,155 --> 00:24:10,588
Just work with me.

251
00:24:10,656 --> 00:24:13,090
But why should I, though?

252
00:24:13,159 --> 00:24:15,354
Because you're a good cop.

253
00:24:15,428 --> 00:24:18,056
How do you know that?

254
00:24:18,131 --> 00:24:19,462
You told me.

255
00:24:19,532 --> 00:24:22,695
Oh. I'm such a good cop.

256
00:24:22,769 --> 00:24:26,728
How come I'm walking
the beat then, at my age?

257
00:24:26,806 --> 00:24:28,740
You want to tell me?

258
00:24:28,808 --> 00:24:32,244
Maybe I'm that whore with a heart of gold

259
00:24:32,311 --> 00:24:34,745
or the one good cop in the bad town.

260
00:24:34,814 --> 00:24:37,715
Is that what you want to hear?

261
00:24:37,784 --> 00:24:41,720
You want to stay on the beat, you do that.

262
00:24:41,788 --> 00:24:45,724
If you'd like to come with me, I need your help.

263
00:24:48,327 --> 00:24:50,420
I'm asking you for help.

264
00:24:54,467 --> 00:24:58,335
Well, it's the thing you fear, isn't it?

265
00:25:01,607 --> 00:25:04,542
Mr. Ness, I wish I'd met you

266
00:25:04,610 --> 00:25:07,044
10 years and 20 pounds ago,

267
00:25:07,113 --> 00:25:12,050
but I just think it got more important to me

268
00:25:12,118 --> 00:25:15,144
to stay alive.

269
00:25:22,261 --> 00:25:25,196
And that's why I'm walking the beat.

270
00:25:25,264 --> 00:25:26,629
Thank you, no.

271
00:25:39,946 --> 00:25:40,970
[Door Closes]

272
00:25:41,047 --> 00:25:42,378
That's good, Andy.

273
00:25:42,448 --> 00:25:45,884
Let's start her up and take a little ride.

274
00:25:45,952 --> 00:25:48,887
I want to hear that Stutz-Bearcat engine.

275
00:25:48,955 --> 00:25:50,388
Let me open the door.

276
00:25:50,456 --> 00:25:53,357
Upsy-Daisy.
Pick up the door there, Andy.

277
00:25:53,426 --> 00:25:54,393
[Laughter]

278
00:25:54,460 --> 00:25:56,394
Throw it in the backseat.

279
00:25:56,462 --> 00:25:58,896
Let me get the thing started.

280
00:25:58,965 --> 00:26:00,398
Yeah, start up.

281
00:26:00,466 --> 00:26:01,899
[Engine Grinds]

282
00:26:01,968 --> 00:26:03,868
[Puffing]

283
00:26:03,936 --> 00:26:05,563
[Engine turns over]

284
00:26:05,638 --> 00:26:07,538
[High-Pitched Squeal]

285
00:26:07,607 --> 00:26:10,542
Holy mackerel, Andy.
Listen to that Bearcat motor.

286
00:26:10,610 --> 00:26:15,047
Yeah. Sound like the bear's
chasing that cat all around.

287
00:26:15,114 --> 00:26:17,105
[Hissing]

288
00:26:17,183 --> 00:26:19,481
Andy, she's boiling over.

289
00:26:30,496 --> 00:26:31,963
Mr. Ness?

290
00:26:32,031 --> 00:26:33,362
Yes.

291
00:26:33,432 --> 00:26:34,865
Oscar Wallace.

292
00:26:36,202 --> 00:26:37,328
Uh-huh.

293
00:26:37,403 --> 00:26:40,497
I've been assigned here by the Washington bureau.

294
00:26:40,573 --> 00:26:41,767
Really?

295
00:26:41,841 --> 00:26:42,899
Yes.

296
00:26:42,975 --> 00:26:46,411
Well, I'm glad to have you here, Mr. Wallace.

297
00:26:46,479 --> 00:26:47,912
Uh, excuse me.

298
00:26:47,980 --> 00:26:50,574
We're a little in the dark here,

299
00:26:50,650 --> 00:26:53,084
but any ideas you may have...

300
00:26:53,152 --> 00:26:55,086
Actually, yes, sir, I do.

301
00:26:55,154 --> 00:26:58,089
The one I want to try first is this.

302
00:27:01,594 --> 00:27:05,826
He has not filed a return since 1926.

303
00:27:07,566 --> 00:27:08,760
A return.

304
00:27:09,936 --> 00:27:11,563
An income tax return.

305
00:27:11,637 --> 00:27:12,899
Income tax.

306
00:27:12,972 --> 00:27:14,405
Yes, sir.

307
00:27:14,473 --> 00:27:17,408
What do you do at the bureau, Mr. Wallace?

308
00:27:17,476 --> 00:27:19,376
Oh, I'm an accountant.

309
00:27:19,445 --> 00:27:20,537
Accountant?

310
00:27:20,613 --> 00:27:24,049
Yes, sir. And the bureau has sent me here...

311
00:27:25,284 --> 00:27:27,013
Would you excuse me?

312
00:27:30,790 --> 00:27:31,722
Please.

313
00:27:58,584 --> 00:28:00,518
O.K., let's go.

314
00:28:00,586 --> 00:28:02,520
Where are we going?

315
00:28:02,588 --> 00:28:05,421
These walls have ears.

316
00:28:07,693 --> 00:28:10,127
You said you wanted to know

317
00:28:10,196 --> 00:28:11,823
how to get Capone.

318
00:28:14,100 --> 00:28:17,035
Do you really want to get him?

319
00:28:17,103 --> 00:28:19,037
You see what I'm saying?

320
00:28:19,105 --> 00:28:22,040
What are you prepared to do?

321
00:28:22,108 --> 00:28:24,133
Everything within the law.

322
00:28:24,210 --> 00:28:26,542
And then what are you prepared to do?

323
00:28:26,612 --> 00:28:29,547
If you open the ball on these people,

324
00:28:29,615 --> 00:28:32,709
you must be prepared to go all the way.

325
00:28:32,785 --> 00:28:34,218
They won't stop fighting

326
00:28:34,286 --> 00:28:36,652
until one of you is dead.

327
00:28:36,722 --> 00:28:38,246
I want to get Capone.

328
00:28:38,324 --> 00:28:40,315
You want Capone?
Here's how.

329
00:28:40,393 --> 00:28:43,328
He pulls a knife, you pull a gun.

330
00:28:43,396 --> 00:28:46,331
He sends one of yours to the hospital,

331
00:28:46,399 --> 00:28:49,334
you send one of his to the morgue.

332
00:28:49,402 --> 00:28:51,336
That's how you get Capone.

333
00:28:52,405 --> 00:28:55,340
Now, do you want to do that?

334
00:28:55,408 --> 00:28:57,842
Are you ready to do that?

335
00:28:59,745 --> 00:29:01,679
I'm making you a deal.

336
00:29:01,747 --> 00:29:04,181
Do you want this deal?

337
00:29:04,250 --> 00:29:07,185
I have sworn to put this man away

338
00:29:07,253 --> 00:29:10,188
with any and all legal means at my disposal,

339
00:29:10,256 --> 00:29:12,019
and I will do so.

340
00:29:20,933 --> 00:29:24,164
Well, the Lord hates a coward.

341
00:29:30,776 --> 00:29:34,405
Do you know what a blood oath is, Mr. Ness?

342
00:29:34,480 --> 00:29:35,412
Yes.

343
00:29:35,481 --> 00:29:37,972
Good. Because you just took one.

344
00:29:39,285 --> 00:29:42,721
How did Capone know about
your raid the other night?

345
00:29:42,788 --> 00:29:44,221
Some cop told him.

346
00:29:44,290 --> 00:29:45,723
Right.
Welcome to Chicago.

347
00:29:45,791 --> 00:29:49,227
This town stinks like a whorehouse at low tide.

348
00:29:49,295 --> 00:29:52,731
Now, the first thing is, who can you trust?

349
00:29:52,798 --> 00:29:53,730
Nobody.

350
00:29:53,799 --> 00:29:54,731
The cops -- nobody.

351
00:29:54,800 --> 00:29:56,734
Because nobody wants you here.

352
00:29:56,802 --> 00:29:59,737
Then why are you helping me?

353
00:29:59,805 --> 00:30:02,740
Because I swore to uphold the law.

354
00:30:02,808 --> 00:30:06,244
And if you believe that, I'll tell you another.

355
00:30:06,312 --> 00:30:08,746
Now, who can you trust?

356
00:30:08,814 --> 00:30:10,247
You trust nobody.

357
00:30:10,316 --> 00:30:11,749
That's the solid truth.

358
00:30:11,817 --> 00:30:14,752
Then where are we going to get help?

359
00:30:14,820 --> 00:30:17,755
If you're afraid of getting a rotten apple,

360
00:30:17,823 --> 00:30:19,757
don't go to the barrel.

361
00:30:19,825 --> 00:30:21,952
Get it off the tree.

362
00:30:23,496 --> 00:30:25,378
Get it off the tree.

363
00:30:25,512 --> 00:30:27,537
[Gunshots]

364
00:30:27,614 --> 00:30:29,548
Finger on the trigger guard!

365
00:30:29,616 --> 00:30:31,049
Eject those cartridges!

366
00:30:31,117 --> 00:30:32,550
Clear it all around!

367
00:30:32,619 --> 00:30:34,052
Stand back!

368
00:30:34,120 --> 00:30:35,644
About face!

369
00:30:35,722 --> 00:30:39,158
Barry, I want you to meet Mr. Eliot Ness.

370
00:30:39,225 --> 00:30:41,159
Treasury Department.
How are you?

371
00:30:41,227 --> 00:30:44,162
We need a recruit for extended duty.

372
00:30:44,230 --> 00:30:47,165
He's to be seconded to the Treasury Department.

373
00:30:47,233 --> 00:30:49,167
We have the cooperation of...

374
00:30:49,235 --> 00:30:52,170
Who is consistently this class' best shot?

375
00:30:52,238 --> 00:30:54,172
Williamson and Stone.

376
00:30:54,240 --> 00:30:55,036
Please call them out...

377
00:30:55,108 --> 00:30:57,042
But one at a time.

378
00:30:57,110 --> 00:30:58,873
Is either man married?

379
00:30:58,945 --> 00:30:59,934
No.

380
00:31:00,013 --> 00:31:01,674
Good.

381
00:31:01,748 --> 00:31:02,680
Williamson!

382
00:31:02,749 --> 00:31:03,681
You're married.

383
00:31:03,750 --> 00:31:06,344
I don't want any married men.

384
00:31:07,420 --> 00:31:09,411
All right.
Stand easy, son.

385
00:31:09,489 --> 00:31:12,117
I want to ask you something.

386
00:31:12,192 --> 00:31:14,592
Why do you want to join the force?

387
00:31:14,661 --> 00:31:16,151
To protect and s-s...

388
00:31:16,229 --> 00:31:18,493
and s... To protect and serve.

389
00:31:18,565 --> 00:31:19,623
To protect...

390
00:31:19,699 --> 00:31:22,634
Please don't search for the yearbook answer.

391
00:31:22,702 --> 00:31:24,067
Say what you think.

392
00:31:24,137 --> 00:31:25,661
Well, what I think?

393
00:31:25,739 --> 00:31:26,671
Yeah.

394
00:31:26,740 --> 00:31:28,173
I could help...

395
00:31:28,241 --> 00:31:30,539
with the force.

396
00:31:30,610 --> 00:31:32,134
You can help?

397
00:31:32,212 --> 00:31:33,144
The force.

398
00:31:33,213 --> 00:31:34,612
With crime.

399
00:31:34,681 --> 00:31:36,308
Thank you.

400
00:31:36,383 --> 00:31:39,250
There goes the next chief of police.

401
00:31:45,425 --> 00:31:47,484
At ease!

402
00:31:47,560 --> 00:31:48,857
Stone.

403
00:31:48,928 --> 00:31:50,520
Out here.

404
00:31:52,265 --> 00:31:53,698
This kid's a prodigy.

405
00:31:55,602 --> 00:31:58,537
Why do you want to join the force?

406
00:31:58,605 --> 00:32:01,540
To protect the property and the citizenry...

407
00:32:01,608 --> 00:32:04,668
Don't waste my time with that bullshit.

408
00:32:04,744 --> 00:32:07,577
Where are you from, Stone?

409
00:32:09,949 --> 00:32:11,416
From the South Side.

410
00:32:11,484 --> 00:32:13,611
Stone.

411
00:32:13,686 --> 00:32:18,521
George Stone.
That's your name?

412
00:32:18,591 --> 00:32:21,253
What's your real name?

413
00:32:21,327 --> 00:32:22,658
That is my real name.

414
00:32:22,729 --> 00:32:26,130
Nah. What was it before you changed it?

415
00:32:28,635 --> 00:32:30,068
Giuseppe Petri.

416
00:32:30,136 --> 00:32:31,603
Jeez, I knew it.

417
00:32:31,671 --> 00:32:34,970
All you need is one thieving wop on the team.

418
00:32:35,041 --> 00:32:37,271
What's that you say?

419
00:32:37,343 --> 00:32:40,278
I said that you're a lying member

420
00:32:40,346 --> 00:32:42,371
of a no-good race.

421
00:32:43,883 --> 00:32:47,751
It's much better than you,
you stinking Irish pig.

422
00:32:49,422 --> 00:32:50,719
Oh, I like him.

423
00:32:53,660 --> 00:32:57,061
Yeah, I like him, too.

424
00:32:57,130 --> 00:33:00,588
You just joined the Treasury Department, son.

425
00:33:00,667 --> 00:33:02,692
Yeah, O.K.

426
00:33:05,138 --> 00:33:06,332
Eliot Ness.

427
00:33:07,674 --> 00:33:10,108
With reports from stakeouts and surveillances...

428
00:33:10,176 --> 00:33:14,237
Thank you, Lieutenant.
Thank you.

429
00:33:22,188 --> 00:33:23,621
What do you think?

430
00:33:23,690 --> 00:33:27,558
I think there's nothing like vaudeville.

431
00:33:27,627 --> 00:33:29,060
That's what I think.

432
00:33:29,129 --> 00:33:32,121
Now, are you ready to go to work?

433
00:33:32,198 --> 00:33:33,631
Where are we going?

434
00:33:33,700 --> 00:33:36,635
On a liquor raid.

435
00:33:36,703 --> 00:33:38,136
We need another man.

436
00:33:38,204 --> 00:33:40,138
Hey, Ness, it's very interesting.

437
00:33:40,206 --> 00:33:43,141
I've found a financial disbursement pattern here

438
00:33:43,209 --> 00:33:44,540
which shows some irregu...

439
00:33:44,611 --> 00:33:45,771
You carry a badge?

440
00:33:45,845 --> 00:33:47,210
Yes.

441
00:33:47,280 --> 00:33:48,542
Carry a gun.

442
00:34:05,431 --> 00:34:06,955
Jimmy?

443
00:34:07,033 --> 00:34:07,965
What?

444
00:34:10,036 --> 00:34:13,062
What the hell are you dressed for, Halloween?

445
00:34:13,139 --> 00:34:15,004
Shut up.
I'm working.

446
00:34:15,074 --> 00:34:15,938
Where?

447
00:34:16,009 --> 00:34:16,976
The circus.

448
00:34:35,261 --> 00:34:36,694
Look.
They've got guns.

449
00:34:38,398 --> 00:34:39,865
Well, here we are.

450
00:34:39,933 --> 00:34:41,366
What are we doing here?

451
00:34:41,434 --> 00:34:42,526
Liquor raid.

452
00:34:45,371 --> 00:34:46,463
Here?

453
00:34:46,539 --> 00:34:49,474
Mr. Ness, everybody knows where the booze is.

454
00:34:49,542 --> 00:34:51,476
The problem isn't finding it.

455
00:34:51,544 --> 00:34:54,069
It's who wants to cross Capone.

456
00:34:54,147 --> 00:34:55,239
Let's go.

457
00:35:03,056 --> 00:35:05,490
You'd better be damn sure, Malone.

458
00:35:10,863 --> 00:35:13,297
If you walk through this door,

459
00:35:13,366 --> 00:35:16,233
you're walking into a world of trouble.

460
00:35:16,302 --> 00:35:18,236
No turning back, you understand?

461
00:35:18,304 --> 00:35:19,828
Yes, I do.

462
00:35:19,906 --> 00:35:21,237
[Cocks Gun]

463
00:35:21,307 --> 00:35:22,934
Good.

464
00:35:23,009 --> 00:35:24,442
Give me that ax.

465
00:35:33,319 --> 00:35:34,547
Federal officers!

466
00:35:34,621 --> 00:35:37,055
Get your hands up!
Nobody moves!

467
00:35:37,123 --> 00:35:38,556
This is a raid!

468
00:35:39,892 --> 00:35:42,087
What are you doing here?

469
00:35:42,161 --> 00:35:44,095
All this stuff is impounded.

470
00:35:44,163 --> 00:35:46,063
You're all under arrest.

471
00:35:46,132 --> 00:35:47,565
Hey, this isn't right.

472
00:35:47,634 --> 00:35:49,568
Hey, this is no good.

473
00:35:49,636 --> 00:35:51,069
You got a warrant?

474
00:35:51,137 --> 00:35:52,934
Sure. Here's my warrant.

475
00:35:55,475 --> 00:35:58,376
How do you think he feels now,

476
00:35:58,444 --> 00:35:59,775
better or worse?

477
00:36:06,519 --> 00:36:07,952
What is that?

478
00:36:08,021 --> 00:36:09,454
What is that?

479
00:36:09,522 --> 00:36:11,319
Yes. What is it?

480
00:36:11,391 --> 00:36:13,325
God, I'm with the heathen.

481
00:36:13,393 --> 00:36:15,759
That is my call box key,

482
00:36:15,828 --> 00:36:17,762
and that is St.Jude.

483
00:36:17,830 --> 00:36:19,764
Santo Judaea.

484
00:36:19,832 --> 00:36:22,767
He's the patron saint of lost causes.

485
00:36:22,835 --> 00:36:23,927
And policemen.

486
00:36:25,705 --> 00:36:27,229
Patron saint of policemen.

487
00:36:27,307 --> 00:36:29,775
Mmm. Everybody needs a friend.

488
00:36:31,244 --> 00:36:33,804
Lost causes, policemen.

489
00:36:33,880 --> 00:36:36,314
Which do you want to be?

490
00:36:36,382 --> 00:36:38,680
I want to be a cop.

491
00:36:38,751 --> 00:36:39,740
You do?

492
00:36:39,819 --> 00:36:40,751
Yeah.

493
00:36:40,820 --> 00:36:41,912
Why?

494
00:36:43,089 --> 00:36:45,922
To protect the property and citizenry...

495
00:36:49,362 --> 00:36:52,263
Who... It's all... It's all right.

496
00:36:52,332 --> 00:36:53,458
What?

497
00:36:53,533 --> 00:36:54,591
Congratulations.

498
00:36:54,667 --> 00:36:59,104
O.K. If I get a picture of you and your men?

499
00:36:59,172 --> 00:37:02,198
Yeah. But not for publication, just for us.

500
00:37:02,275 --> 00:37:04,209
Anything you say, Mr. Ness.

501
00:37:05,345 --> 00:37:07,723
Closer in.
Arms straight.

502
00:37:07,857 --> 00:37:08,755
O.K., ready? Hold it.

503
00:37:16,699 --> 00:37:18,257
Life goes on.

504
00:37:18,334 --> 00:37:20,598
[Laughter]

505
00:37:22,972 --> 00:37:24,405
A man becomes preeminent,

506
00:37:24,473 --> 00:37:28,000
he's expected to have enthusiasms.

507
00:37:28,077 --> 00:37:29,601
Enthusiasms.

508
00:37:31,380 --> 00:37:32,847
Enthusiasms.

509
00:37:34,984 --> 00:37:36,417
What are mine?

510
00:37:37,920 --> 00:37:39,353
What draws my admiration?

511
00:37:39,422 --> 00:37:42,357
What is that which gives me joy?

512
00:37:42,425 --> 00:37:44,086
- Dames.
- Music.

513
00:37:48,597 --> 00:37:49,859
Baseball.

514
00:37:56,739 --> 00:37:58,229
A man...

515
00:37:58,307 --> 00:38:01,242
A man stands alone at a plate.

516
00:38:04,246 --> 00:38:07,579
This is the time for what?

517
00:38:07,650 --> 00:38:10,244
For individual achievement.

518
00:38:12,688 --> 00:38:14,451
There he stands alone.

519
00:38:15,825 --> 00:38:19,124
But in the field, what?

520
00:38:19,195 --> 00:38:21,789
Part of a team.

521
00:38:21,864 --> 00:38:23,525
Teamwork.

522
00:38:23,599 --> 00:38:25,157
Teamwork.

523
00:38:27,670 --> 00:38:31,333
Looks, throws, catches, hustles...

524
00:38:31,407 --> 00:38:33,602
Part of one big team.

525
00:38:33,676 --> 00:38:36,668
Bats himself the livelong day.

526
00:38:36,746 --> 00:38:39,681
Babe Ruth, Ty Cobb, and so on.

527
00:38:41,150 --> 00:38:45,519
If his team don't field, what is he?

528
00:38:47,857 --> 00:38:49,290
You follow me?

529
00:38:49,358 --> 00:38:50,916
No one.

530
00:38:52,628 --> 00:38:55,597
Sunny day, the stands are full of fans.

531
00:38:55,664 --> 00:38:58,098
What does he have to say?

532
00:38:59,568 --> 00:39:02,093
I'm going out there for myself.

533
00:39:03,539 --> 00:39:05,473
But...

534
00:39:05,541 --> 00:39:10,035
I get nowhere unless the team wins.

535
00:39:10,112 --> 00:39:11,204
Team.

536
00:39:11,280 --> 00:39:12,975
- Yeah, team.
- Team.

